-- 24-proof-carrying-code.cell
-- Merge two sorted lists into one sorted list.
-- Generate code + formal correctness argument. Validate argument structure.
-- If gap: regenerate that part. Code + proof ship together.
--
-- Tests: proof-carrying computation, ‚ä¢‚àò evolution loop on proof gaps,
--        ‚ä¢= crystallized verifiers, oracle-gated correctness, ¬ß quotation
--
-- Cell's killer pattern: LLM generates code+proof (NP), crystallized
-- verifier structurally checks the proof (P). Gaps trigger regeneration.

‚ä¢ spec
  given description ‚â° "merge two sorted lists into one sorted list"
  given signature ‚â° "merge_sorted(a: int[], b: int[]) -> int[]"
  given preconditions ‚â° "a is sorted ascending, b is sorted ascending"
  given postconditions ‚â° "result is sorted ascending, result is a permutation of a ++ b"
  yield description, signature, preconditions, postconditions

  ‚ä® description specifies the algorithm, inputs, and output
  ‚ä® signature has typed parameters and return type
  ‚ä® preconditions constrain both input lists
  ‚ä® postconditions specify sortedness and permutation properties

‚ä¢ generate-code
  given spec‚Üídescription
  given spec‚Üísignature
  given spec‚Üípreconditions
  yield ¬ßimplementation, code-text

  ‚à¥ Write a correct implementation of ¬´spec‚Üísignature¬ª that satisfies:
    ¬´spec‚Üídescription¬ª
    Preconditions: ¬´spec‚Üípreconditions¬ª

    Use a two-pointer merge algorithm. Walk both lists simultaneously,
    always appending the smaller head element. When one list is exhausted,
    append the remainder of the other. The implementation must:
    - Maintain two indices i, j starting at 0
    - Compare a[i] vs b[j], append the smaller, advance that pointer
    - Handle exhaustion of either list
    - Return the merged result

    Output the code as a Cell ‚ä¢= expression.

  ‚ä® code-text contains a loop or iterative structure
  ‚ä® code-text compares elements from both lists
  ‚ä® code-text handles the case when one list is exhausted before the other

‚ä¢ generate-tests
  given spec‚Üísignature
  given spec‚Üípreconditions
  given spec‚Üípostconditions
  yield test-cases[], properties[]

  ‚à¥ Generate test cases for ¬´spec‚Üísignature¬ª.

    Properties to test:
    1. Sorted output: result must be in ascending order
    2. Permutation: result contains exactly the elements of a ++ b
    3. Length: len(result) = len(a) + len(b)
    4. Empty left: merge([], b) = b
    5. Empty right: merge(a, []) = a
    6. Both empty: merge([], []) = []
    7. Interleaved: elements from a and b alternate in result
    8. Duplicates: repeated values across lists handled correctly

    For each property, generate 2-3 concrete test cases with
    { input-a, input-b, expected-output }.

  ‚ä® length(test-cases) ‚â• 12
  ‚ä® properties covers sorted, permutation, empty, and duplicate cases
  ‚ä® each test-case has input-a (sorted), input-b (sorted), and expected-output (sorted)

‚ä¢ run-tests
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  given generate-tests‚Üítest-cases
  yield results[], pass-count, fail-count, failure-details[]

  ‚à¥ Simulate executing ¬´generate-code‚Üícode-text¬ª on each test case
    in ¬´generate-tests‚Üítest-cases¬ª. For each test:
    - Trace through the merge with the given inputs
    - Record the actual output
    - Compare to expected-output
    - If mismatch: record failure with pointer positions showing divergence

  ‚ä® length(results) = length(generate-tests‚Üítest-cases)
  ‚ä® pass-count + fail-count = length(results)
  ‚ä® if fail-count > 0 then length(failure-details) = fail-count

‚ä¢ generate-proof
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  given spec‚Üípreconditions
  given spec‚Üípostconditions
  given run-tests‚Üípass-count
  yield proof-argument, invariants[], termination-argument, properties-proved[]

  ‚à¥ Given the code ¬´generate-code‚Üícode-text¬ª that passes ¬´run-tests‚Üípass-count¬ª
    tests, generate a formal correctness argument.

    The proof must establish:
    1. **Loop invariant**: At each step, result[0..k] is sorted and contains
       exactly the elements taken so far from a[0..i] and b[0..j].
    2. **Sortedness preservation**: Since a[i] ‚â§ a[i+1] and b[j] ‚â§ b[j+1],
       appending min(a[i], b[j]) maintains sorted order in result.
    3. **Permutation**: Every element of a and b appears exactly once in result.
       i + j = k at each step; final k = len(a) + len(b).
    4. **Termination**: i + j increases by 1 each iteration, bounded by
       len(a) + len(b). Loop terminates when both lists exhausted.
    5. **Postcondition**: At termination, result is sorted ‚àß result is
       permutation of a ++ b. Follows from invariant + termination.

    Express each step as a logical proposition with justification.

  ‚ä® proof-argument contains at least 5 logical steps
  ‚ä® invariants includes a loop invariant referencing i, j, and result
  ‚ä® termination-argument identifies a quantity that increases monotonically
  ‚ä® properties-proved includes "sortedness" and "permutation"

‚ä¢ verify-proof ‚ñ∏ crystallized
  given generate-proof‚Üíproof-argument
  given generate-proof‚Üíinvariants
  given generate-proof‚Üítermination-argument
  given generate-proof‚Üíproperties-proved
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  yield proof-valid, gaps[], verdict

  ‚ä¢= proof-valid ‚Üê (
    has-loop-invariant(invariants) ‚àß
    invariant-references(invariants, ["i", "j", "result"]) ‚àß
    has-monotone-quantity(termination-argument) ‚àß
    has-upper-bound(termination-argument) ‚àß
    proof-covers(proof-argument, ["sortedness", "permutation", "termination"]) ‚àß
    proof-uses-precondition(proof-argument, "sorted")
  )

  ‚ä¢= gaps ‚Üê missing-from(proof-argument, [
    "loop-invariant", "sortedness-preservation", "permutation",
    "termination", "postcondition-discharge"
  ])

  ‚ä¢= verdict ‚Üê if proof-valid ‚àß gaps = [] then "proof complete"
                else if proof-valid then "proof valid with gaps"
                else "proof incomplete"

  ‚ä® verdict ‚àà {"proof complete", "proof valid with gaps", "proof incomplete"}
  ‚ä® if proof-valid then gaps has at most 1 element
  ‚ä® if not proof-valid then length(gaps) ‚â• 2

‚ä¢ fill-gaps
  given verify-proof‚Üígaps
  given verify-proof‚Üíverdict
  given generate-proof‚Üíproof-argument
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  given spec‚Üípreconditions
  yield proof-patch, patched-steps[]

  ‚à¥ If ¬´verify-proof‚Üíverdict¬ª = "proof complete", output
    proof-patch ‚â° "none" and patched-steps ‚â° [].

    Otherwise, for each gap in ¬´verify-proof‚Üígaps¬ª:
    - Identify what the proof is missing
    - Write the missing argument step, referencing ¬´generate-code‚Üícode-text¬ª
      and ¬´spec‚Üípreconditions¬ª
    - Each patched step must be a self-contained logical argument

    The patch is ADDITIVE ‚Äî it supplements the existing proof, not replaces it.

  ‚ä® if verify-proof‚Üíverdict = "proof complete" then proof-patch = "none"
  ‚ä® if verify-proof‚Üíverdict ‚âÝ "proof complete" then length(patched-steps) = length(verify-proof‚Üígaps)
  ‚ä® each patched-step references the specific gap it addresses

‚ä¢‚àò evolve(generate-proof, spec‚Üípreconditions ‚â° spec‚Üípreconditions)
  through verify-proof, fill-gaps
  until verify-proof‚Üíverdict = "proof complete"
  max 3

  -- Each iteration: generate proof ‚Üí verify structure ‚Üí fill gaps.
  -- The gap-fills feed back into the proof for re-verification.
  --
  -- Interface frozen: generate-proof always takes code-text,
  -- preconditions, postconditions, pass-count. Only the argument evolves.
  --
  -- Termination: when proof is complete (no gaps) or max 3 iterations.

‚ä¢ assemble-certificate
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  given fill-gaps‚Üíproof-patch
  given generate-proof‚Üíproof-argument
  given generate-proof‚Üíproperties-proved
  given verify-proof‚Üíverdict
  given verify-proof‚Üígaps
  given run-tests‚Üípass-count
  yield certificate, confidence-level

  ‚à¥ Assemble a proof-carrying certificate for ¬´generate-code‚Üícode-text¬ª:

    Certificate contains:
    1. The verified merge implementation
    2. The correctness argument (original + patches)
    3. Test results: ¬´run-tests‚Üípass-count¬ª tests passing
    4. Proof verification verdict: ¬´verify-proof‚Üíverdict¬ª
    5. Remaining gaps (if any): ¬´verify-proof‚Üígaps¬ª
    6. Properties proved: ¬´generate-proof‚Üíproperties-proved¬ª

    Confidence level:
    - "high" if verdict = "proof complete" and pass-count ‚â• 12
    - "medium" if verdict = "proof valid with gaps" and pass-count ‚â• 8
    - "low" if verdict = "proof incomplete" or pass-count < 8

    This certificate is the deliverable: code + proof ship together.
    The LLM generated the solution (NP). The crystallized verifier
    checked the proof structure (P). Tests provide empirical evidence.

  ‚ä® certificate includes code, proof, test-count, verdict, and properties-proved
  ‚ä® confidence-level ‚àà {"high", "medium", "low"}
  ‚ä® if verify-proof‚Üíverdict = "proof complete" and run-tests‚Üípass-count ‚â• 12 then confidence-level = "high"

‚ä®? on failure:
  retry with ¬´oracle.failures¬ª max 3
‚ä®? on exhaustion:
  partial-accept(best)
